Monster Codex, the "Inner Seas Races," the "Burnt
Offerings," the "We be goblins" set, the goblin

00:07:49.002 --> 00:07:52.251
promo figure, the town square flip mat, goblin
bank, goblin plush, a whole bunch of crazy stuff.

00:07:52.251 --> 00:07:56.282
So, big old grand prize for one of you guys out
there, so make sure you're engaging.

00:07:56.346 --> 00:07:57.406
IVAN: Yeah.

00:07:57.406 --> 00:07:59.208
MATT: Anyway. Now that that's over with--

00:07:59.208 --> 00:08:00.115
PHIL: Woo!

00:08:00.115 --> 00:08:02.795
(laughter)

00:08:02.795 --> 00:08:06.995
MATT: For tonight's game, you guys will be playing
goblins, of course. I'll go over the story here in

00:08:07.146 --> 00:08:11.564
a moment, but things to consider: part of
tonight's fun is, at certain points during the

00:08:11.564 --> 00:08:18.510
story, if you roll really crappily on a roll, or
you want to get that extra action in, you're doing

00:08:18.510 --> 00:08:23.867
good and you want to get that extra attack or
extra ability, each of you have constructed and

00:08:23.867 --> 00:08:29.361
have at your disposal a goblin song that is custom
to your character. You may choose to sing this

00:08:29.361 --> 00:08:34.752
song out loud on the stream and doing so will gain
use of that reroll or that extra action. Use it

00:08:34.752 --> 00:08:38.858
sparingly, it's only once in a while, possibly a
once-a-night type circumstance. But I'm exci--

00:08:38.858 --> 00:08:42.563
(burps) pardon, I'm excited to hear all of your
individual songs as we progress.

00:08:42.563 --> 00:08:44.935
MARISHA: So excited, it gave him indigestion.

00:08:44.935 --> 00:08:52.487
MATT: It's how it's the reaction, I get nervous,
guys. Great. So, that being the case, let's go

00:08:52.487 --> 00:08:55.112
ahead and get this show on the road.

00:08:55.112 --> 00:08:56.556
MARISHA: Oh my god, I'm so excited.

00:08:56.556 --> 00:08:58.075
IVAN: There we go. Goblin pants!

00:08:58.075 --> 00:09:02.837
MARISHA: Also, I'm using Liam's dice box because
he's not here, and he can't stop it.

00:09:02.837 --> 00:09:04.638
(laughter)

00:09:04.638 --> 00:09:07.320
IVAN: Liam, I'm touching your stuff, I'm touching
your stuff.

00:09:07.320 --> 00:09:09.254
MARISHA: I'm going to rub my butt on it.

00:09:09.254 --> 00:09:21.327
MATT: Here in the Sandpoint Hinterlands, nestled
in the western side of the Devil's Platter

00:09:21.327 --> 00:09:27.445
Mountain Range, there lies the Bird-Cruncher Tribe
of rather rambunctious goblins known for their

00:09:27.445 --> 00:09:31.607
deft trapping skills, having earned their name and
the majority of their food supply by snaring wild

00:09:31.607 --> 00:09:38.769
birds and eating them raw. You five have grown up
together here among the caves and cliffs over the

00:09:38.769 --> 00:09:44.538
past six years, outliving many of your other
brethren, making you tough. Although most of you

00:09:44.538 --> 00:09:49.987
were the runts, discarded as weak and useless, you
were all taken in and raised within your cages,

00:09:49.987 --> 00:09:54.548
which is how most goblins are raised, by the
sagely Guffeye.

00:09:54.548 --> 00:09:55.752
IVAN: Guffeye.

00:09:55.752 --> 00:10:01.405
MATT: An ancient goblin oracle of nearly 30
years of age, who enjoyed the idea of having her

00:10:01.405 --> 00:10:10.821
own troop of personal guardians, she shouts that
she is touched by the sight of Zogmugot, Lady

00:10:10.821 --> 00:10:16.451
Last-Breath and the goblin hero-god of flotsam and
scavenging, though many of her visions have led to

00:10:16.451 --> 00:10:23.157
grave misfortune and her favor within the tribe has
waned. But you guys believe her! Mostly.

00:10:23.157 --> 00:10:29.406
IVAN: Zogmugot looks favorably upon our lovely
Guffeye.

00:10:29.406 --> 00:10:37.205
MATT: This cold, overcast autumn morning rolls in,
and the five of you are returning from a morning

00:10:37.205 --> 00:10:47.569
snare run, when you hear the sound of crackling
shouts from old Guffeye's crag porch. "Come! Come!

00:10:47.569 --> 00:10:50.879
"The dream! The sight! Come!"

00:10:50.879 --> 00:10:53.412
And she darts back into her little cave
hole.

00:10:53.412 --> 00:10:57.668
IVAN: Guffeye has another dream! You know what
that means!

00:10:57.668 --> 00:11:00.366
PHIL: Someone's going to lose a hand.

00:11:00.366 --> 00:11:04.620
MARISHA: Usually this means she's been drinking, I
just want to point that out.

00:11:04.620 --> 00:11:10.367
IVAN: Well, let's go see what the old windbag's up
to, because you know it's going to involve us

00:11:10.367 --> 00:11:11.457
probably dying.

00:11:11.457 --> 00:11:12.845
PHIL: Probably.

00:11:12.845 --> 00:11:14.242
MARISHA: Let's go!

00:11:14.242 --> 00:11:20.618
MATT: Entering her home, the familiar smell of
pungent spices and rotting wood hits your nose,

00:11:20.618 --> 00:11:27.746
and this hoarder hole of a home is crammed to the
brim with driftwood, molded leather, metal scraps,

00:11:27.746 --> 00:11:32.682
torn hides, broken pottery, all sorts of other
beautiful pieces of junk.

00:11:32.682 --> 00:11:33.880
IVAN: It's amazing.

00:11:33.880 --> 00:11:39.261
MATT: Nostalgia comes over you as you glance at
the empty iron cages you once grew up in, now

00:11:39.261 --> 00:11:46.043
partially buried and filled with wet wool. As you
guys enter, old Guffeye steps onto a small box and

00:11:46.043 --> 00:11:55.407
turns, her snow-blind eyes clouded and bulging
above her toothy grin: "My runts! The Lady gifts

00:11:55.407 --> 00:12:07.619
"Guffeye. The wait is broken! I have a vision once
more. A thing, a great thing was shown to Guffeye,

00:12:07.619 --> 00:12:23.215
"in both these eyes: a stone of crack and thoom! A
rock that barks like the storm! This rock, this

00:12:23.215 --> 00:12:36.304
"stone, Guffeye must have! This Guffeye must get!
You! You must get this stone, bring it to me, for

00:12:36.304 --> 00:12:39.854
"the Lady's blessing."

00:12:39.854 --> 00:12:43.250
ASHLY: Guffeye, if I give it to you first will you
like me the best?

00:12:43.250 --> 00:12:46.110
MATT: "I already like you the best--"

00:12:46.110 --> 00:12:46.990
ASHLY: Yes!

00:12:46.990 --> 00:12:50.007
MATT: "--but I will like you twice best."

00:12:50.007 --> 00:12:51.660
ASHLY: Oh my God.

00:12:51.660 --> 00:12:57.755
IVAN: Guffeye, as your esteemed and most
intellectual advisor, I have to ask: where did the

00:12:57.755 --> 00:13:01.070
Lady bestow this vision upon you that we may find
the barking rock?

00:13:01.070 --> 00:13:08.682
MATT: "Well, I awoke this morning, envisioning
just how much more I like Piglet than the rest of you--"

00:13:08.682 --> 00:13:12.409
IVAN: But I just got done scrubbing all of your
sores last night!

00:13:12.409 --> 00:13:13.597
MATT: "Silence!"

00:13:13.597 --> 00:13:15.254
ASHLY: Sorry, Guffeye.

00:13:15.254 --> 00:13:22.207
MATT: "Upon brewing my morning thatch tea, the
vision struck my face! I dropped it, it shattered,

00:13:22.207 --> 00:13:31.829
"in a beautiful clattering of broken pottery, and I
saw before me a reminder that today is a special

00:13:31.829 --> 00:13:43.413
"day. The sun. The sun rise highest in the sky!
Today is the day of the human festival in

00:13:43.413 --> 00:13:56.518
"Sandpoint-- filthy, stupid human festival! The
Lady showed me a man. A man in blue, blue

00:13:56.518 --> 00:14:03.440
"everywhere, in robes, a church man." (spits)

00:14:03.440 --> 00:14:05.663
(spitting)

00:14:05.663 --> 00:14:13.899
MATT: "His name was Zaan-- Hold on."

00:14:13.899 --> 00:14:16.052
ALL: Zaan?

00:14:16.052 --> 00:14:19.667
MATT: "Zaan-- Zantos."

00:14:19.667 --> 00:14:22.614
ALL: Zantos!

00:14:22.614 --> 00:14:35.956
MATT: "Guffeye saw the people around the churchman
at this festival-- the churchman has the storm

00:14:35.956 --> 00:14:37.981
"rock on him!"

00:14:37.981 --> 00:14:40.681
IVAN: Ooh, storm rock.

00:14:40.681 --> 00:14:53.835
MATT: "So. Go to this Sandpoint. Go to this human
festival. Find this blue-skinned, blue-robed

00:14:53.835 --> 00:14:57.790
"church-man and take the stone for Guffeye, yes?"

00:14:57.790 --> 00:15:02.939
ASHLY: That sounds pretty easy, like nothing bad
will happen?

00:15:02.939 --> 00:15:04.884
IVAN: Easy! Exactly! We got this!

00:15:04.884 --> 00:15:12.152
MATT: "The Lady also showed me: other goblins
know."

00:15:12.152 --> 00:15:13.099
MARISHA: What?!

00:15:13.099 --> 00:15:21.128
MATT: "Stupid, stupid Seven-Tooth tribe also wants
stone, going to city now!"

00:15:21.128 --> 00:15:24.096
IVAN: Why would the Lady show them the blue
stone?

00:15:24.096 --> 00:15:26.215
TALIESIN: Four tooth too many, that's--

00:15:26.215 --> 00:15:29.227
IVAN: Seven tooth too much, two tooth is best
tooth!

00:15:29.227 --> 00:15:30.757
MARISHA: I agree, I agree.

00:15:30.757 --> 00:15:32.118
IVAN: Two tooth is best tooth.

00:15:32.118 --> 00:15:41.178
MATT: "You go. Sneak in! Find churchman! Take
storm rock before Seven-Tooth dumb-dumbs! Bring

00:15:41.178 --> 00:15:46.239
"back to Guffeye, get blessing-- and good meal,
promise."

00:15:46.239 --> 00:15:48.874
PHIL: Oh, well, if there's food--

00:15:48.874 --> 00:15:50.389
TALIESIN: And drink.

00:15:50.389 --> 00:15:57.156
MARISHA: Yeah! Only with a good meal and a drink!
You got it?

00:15:57.156 --> 00:15:59.455
MATT: "This I can provide."

00:15:59.455 --> 00:16:00.708
ASHLY: And dessert?

00:16:00.708 --> 00:16:01.906
MARISHA: Yeah!

00:16:01.906 --> 00:16:04.656
MATT: "Piglet, you're now second most favorite."

00:16:04.656 --> 00:16:07.965
ASHLY: (wailing) No! I didn't mean it! I don't
want dessert!

00:16:07.965 --> 00:16:11.164
PHIL: Greed diminishes you.

00:16:11.164 --> 00:16:13.116
ASHLY: (crying)

00:16:13.116 --> 00:16:15.517
MATT: "Bring me stone, become first favorite!"

00:16:15.517 --> 00:16:16.867
ASHLY: Okay, okay.

00:16:16.867 --> 00:16:19.708
MATT: "Now go! Time is wasting!"

00:16:19.708 --> 00:16:27.578
IVAN: (singing) Blue stone, blue stone, we will
get it all! Blue stone, blue stone, then we'll eat

00:16:27.578 --> 00:16:33.905
them all! Stupid Seven-tooth is going to burn and
burn and die! Burn them all, burn burn, burn and

00:16:33.905 --> 00:16:35.575
burn and die. Yay!

00:16:35.575 --> 00:16:41.705
MATT: (laughs) As you guys exit the cavern, you go
to your various hidey-holes, gather all your

00:16:41.705 --> 00:16:47.796
materials, your weaponry, whatever things you
think you may require on this journey. You know

00:16:47.796 --> 00:16:52.637
that the direction is northwest, past the
Ravenroost mountain pass, towards this town of

00:16:52.637 --> 00:16:58.642
Sandpoint, and that is where your path lies. The
clouds begin to gather overhead at this point in time.

00:16:58.642 --> 00:17:00.577
IVAN: Ooh. Best weather for scavenging!

00:17:00.577 --> 00:17:03.074
PHIL: Nice and clammy.

00:17:03.074 --> 00:17:06.523
IVAN: They won't even see us coming! Because we're
goblins.

00:17:06.523 --> 00:17:10.793
MATT: A gentle rain slowly begins to hit down from
the sky above.

00:17:10.793 --> 00:17:20.333
IVAN: How long is it going to take for us to get
to Sandpoint?

00:17:20.333 --> 00:17:26.232
MATT: Depends on who's the best leader to find
their way there. I guess--

00:17:26.232 --> 00:17:27.907
IVAN: Grizznak is best leader!

00:17:27.907 --> 00:17:29.183
ASHLY: I am best leader!

00:17:29.183 --> 00:17:30.437
IVAN: Grizznak is smarter!

00:17:30.437 --> 00:17:32.147
PHIL: Which way do your feet point?

00:17:32.147 --> 00:17:34.668
MARISHA: Whoever said you were the smartest?

00:17:34.668 --> 00:17:41.663
IVAN: Because I am the wizard, and the wizard is
always the smartest! This is simple goblin logic!

00:17:41.663 --> 00:17:44.542
MARISHA: That is pretty good logic. I agree with
that.

00:17:44.542 --> 00:17:48.693
ASHLY: But I have a big hammer!

00:17:48.693 --> 00:17:50.497
IVAN: But you are-- look--

00:17:50.497 --> 00:17:52.701
TALIESIN: She does have a big hammer, she has a
very fair point.

00:17:52.701 --> 00:17:59.250
IVAN: Guffeye already tells you that you are the
most elite of Guffeye. So we don't want to soil

00:17:59.250 --> 00:18:08.054
poor Piglet into having you out at front, best to
let Snizzler and Grizznak lead the way.

00:18:08.054 --> 00:18:10.552
TALIESIN: You're the most complete, you heard him,
that's absolutely true.

00:18:10.552 --> 00:18:13.212
MARISHA: I agree with that, yeah. You don't want
to tarnish your beautiful, shining reputation.

00:18:13.212 --> 00:18:15.903
ASHLY: You're right. She would be so sad if I
died.

00:18:15.903 --> 00:18:20.053
TALIESIN: Tarnish the, tarnish the handle of the--
yeah, it's--

00:18:20.053 --> 00:18:23.694
ASHLY: Yeah, that's true. She wouldn't care if you
guys died, but if I died she'd probably be sad.

00:18:23.694 --> 00:18:25.013
MARISHA: Exactly, exactly!

00:18:25.013 --> 00:18:28.659
PHIL: Besides, whoever is in front is most likely
to be shot in the face with something.

00:18:28.659 --> 00:18:32.311
MARISHA: Right, so, naturally, we're better to
lead. Am I right, Grizz?

00:18:32.311 --> 00:18:35.301
IVAN: Yeah, you got it Snizzler. Grizz'n'Snizz,
all the way!

00:18:35.301 --> 00:18:36.527
MARISHA: Grizz'n'Snizz!

00:18:36.527 --> 00:18:41.028
IVAN: So I'm assuming I'm going to make some
navigation--

00:18:41.028 --> 00:18:45.728
MATT: I would like for you to make a survival
check, as the leader of his group.

00:18:45.728 --> 00:18:47.400
IVAN: Haha, yes, leader!

00:18:47.400 --> 00:18:49.507
MARISHA: Grizz or Snizz?

00:18:49.507 --> 00:18:51.600
MATT: Well, whoever one is leading.

00:18:51.600 --> 00:18:53.653
MARISHA: Well, he's leading.

00:18:53.653 --> 00:18:58.619
IVAN: I'm clearly the most intelligent goblin in
this troupe.

00:18:58.619 --> 00:19:00.695
MARISHA: Oh boy, you're so smart.

00:19:00.695 --> 00:19:04.004
ASHLY: Do I smell mutiny already?

00:19:04.004 --> 00:19:06.309
PHIL: I think I smell lunch.

00:19:06.309 --> 00:19:11.896
IVAN: But I think, I don't know if I want to burn
my song already.

00:19:11.896 --> 00:19:21.631
MARISHA: Look, Grizz, look. I'm really good at
building things, so naturally I know how to

00:19:21.631 --> 00:19:22.962
survive better.

00:19:22.962 --> 00:19:24.728
IVAN: You did make the best lean-to.

00:19:24.728 --> 00:19:27.449
MARISHA: I did, I did, in the Boy Scouts.

00:19:27.449 --> 00:19:31.450
IVAN: We went to juvie together.

00:19:31.450 --> 00:19:36.883
MARISHA: We did. Good times. Can I try?

00:19:36.883 --> 00:19:42.022
MATT: Well, we'll say you let (laughs) you let him
lead for a while.

00:19:42.022 --> 00:19:43.199
MARISHA: All right.

00:19:43.199 --> 00:19:46.673
MATT: As you start heading northwest, as you begin
to pass the south part of the Ravenroost mountain

00:19:46.673 --> 00:19:56.158
pass, you're led into a relatively thick patch of
very, very painful bramble thicket chunk.

00:19:56.158 --> 00:19:58.322
IVAN: Underbrush is the best!

00:19:58.322 --> 00:20:01.412
ASHLY: I'm beginning to regret rescinding my offer
to be the leader!

00:20:01.412 --> 00:20:06.246
IVAN: Everyone knows-- goblins know that the most
painful path is usually the right path!

00:20:06.246 --> 00:20:11.363
MATT: And the most painful path does manage to
deal two points of damage to all of you as across

00:20:11.363 --> 00:20:14.986
your flesh being dragged through the bramble
thicket.

00:20:14.986 --> 00:20:18.449
MARSIHA: That's only your own self-loathing,
Grizz, Jesus! Ow!

00:20:18.449 --> 00:20:20.053
ASHLY: I could use a writing utensil.

00:20:20.053 --> 00:20:21.334
IVAN: Oh, that hurts.

00:20:21.334 --> 00:20:26.928
MATT: Until eventually Snizzler decides to rise up
in frustration and take over the leader position.

00:20:26.928 --> 00:20:30.149
MARISHA: Jeez, all right, come on. Let me see.

00:20:30.149 --> 00:20:33.731
IVAN: Here, take dick bone, that is the leader
staff.

00:20:33.731 --> 00:20:38.824
MARISHA: All right, thank you. We got it from an
old badger.

00:20:38.824 --> 00:20:41.442
MATT: Go ahead and make your survival check.

00:20:41.442 --> 00:20:43.123
IVAN: I swear this is best.

00:20:43.123 --> 00:20:48.176
ASHLY: Oh no. That's not a good reaction.

00:20:48.176 --> 00:20:49.284
MATT: So?

00:20:49.284 --> 00:20:51.206
MARISHA: I rolled a natural one.

00:20:51.206 --> 00:20:56.743
TALIESIN: And they were never seen or heard from
again. Game over!

00:20:56.743 --> 00:20:58.253
MATT: Well done!

00:20:58.253 --> 00:21:01.742
IVAN: We're running the best goblin scenario ever
right now.

00:21:01.742 --> 00:21:04.845
MARISHA: Are they going to make it out of the
brush?

00:21:04.845 --> 00:21:07.324
TALIESIN: Like brownies and willow, man, we're
done for.

00:21:07.324 --> 00:21:14.698
MATT: Wading deeper and deeper into the bramble
thicket, now under the guidance of Snizzler.

00:21:14.698 --> 00:21:17.207
MARISHA: Look, it's just about finding the flow.

00:21:17.207 --> 00:21:20.976
PHIL: The flow is up my buttocks!

00:21:20.976 --> 00:21:24.645
MATT: You all take an additional one point of
piercing damage as you're

00:21:24.645 --> 00:21:26.772
scratching your way through.

00:21:26.772 --> 00:21:31.320
IVAN: It hurt! Guys, guys, I don't know, but I
think I have one more rash that I didn't have

00:21:31.320 --> 00:21:33.306
previously somewhere.

00:21:33.306 --> 00:21:36.335
MARISHA: Oh, jeez, there's poison oak everywhere!

00:21:36.335 --> 00:21:42.028
MATT: The rain intensifies, starting to echo
through the mountain ranges in the distance, the

00:21:42.028 --> 00:21:48.201
storm appears to be getting relatively stronger.
However, during this travel the rain that is

00:21:48.201 --> 00:21:52.935
washing down the side of the mountain does lead
you to a position of the thicket that isn't quite

00:21:52.935 --> 00:21:56.271
so heavy, and eventually you guys make your way
outside of the immediate

00:21:56.271 --> 00:21:58.136
physical danger of the terrain.

00:21:58.136 --> 00:22:01.338
PHIL: Congratulations.

00:22:01.338 --> 00:22:03.939
TALIESIN: There's got to be some cover around
here.

00:22:03.939 --> 00:22:05.927
MARISHA: I think we're further than we started.

00:22:05.927 --> 00:22:09.892
IVAN: See, at least we're not at the cave
anymore.

00:22:09.892 --> 00:22:14.344
ASHLY: Piglet doesn't like lightning. Can we go
somewhere where there's no lightning?

00:22:14.344 --> 00:22:15.576
MARISHA: Okay.

00:22:15.576 --> 00:22:22.284
IVAN: Well, are we close to a tree? Because trees
are really good to have cover under lightning, I'm told.

00:22:22.284 --> 00:22:26.416
ASHLY: I wasn't sure whether or not you were the
smartest, but that's the best logic I've heard all day.

00:22:26.416 --> 00:22:29.284
MARISHA: I agree! I agree! You kill it every time,
Grizz!

00:22:29.284 --> 00:22:33.250
IVAN: That's why I'm the wizard! (singing) That's
why they call me the greatest!

00:22:33.250 --> 00:22:35.049
MARISHA: You always did read the most.

00:22:35.049 --> 00:22:37.162
PHIL: You call you the greatest. No one else calls
you that!

00:22:37.162 --> 00:22:38.839
IVAN: Well, Grizznak is the greatest.

00:22:38.839 --> 00:22:42.010
MATT: At which point, a large bolt of lightning
hits a tree maybe about 20 feet off from

00:22:42.010 --> 00:22:47.863
you, sending sparks flying, the tree bursts into
flames and tumbles onto the ground. I need--

00:22:47.863 --> 00:22:50.843
MARISHA: Holy shit! Did you see that, dude?!

00:22:50.843 --> 00:22:54.391
IVAN: Look! Look! Zarongel smiles upon us! See,
he's lit our way!

00:22:54.391 --> 00:22:56.648
ASHLY: You said that lightning didn't like trees!

00:22:56.648 --> 00:23:00.318
MARISHA: That was rad, bro! Oh yeah!

00:23:00.318 --> 00:23:02.276
ASHLY: I don't know about these guys...

00:23:02.276 --> 00:23:09.241
IVAN: So, with no cover and nothing around it I
have a feeling maybe we should make a mad dash for

00:23:09.241 --> 00:23:13.232
either caves or potentially Sandpoint. We're not
anywhere close to Sandpoint--

00:23:13.232 --> 00:23:16.648
MATT: You've done a few loops in the area--

00:23:16.648 --> 00:23:17.825
ASHLY: We've been looping?!

00:23:17.825 --> 00:23:20.791
MATT: Did anybody else want to try and lead this
expedition?

00:23:20.791 --> 00:23:25.392
TALIESIN: Did you want to go which way-- no, I
know which way! I'm going to go! And I'm going to

00:23:25.392 --> 00:23:27.057
walk in a direction. Follow me!

00:23:27.057 --> 00:23:28.678
MATT: All right, Mezek.

00:23:28.678 --> 00:23:30.264
MARISHA: I love family outings.

00:23:30.264 --> 00:23:33.558
TALIESIN: What am I rolling? I just rolled, what
do I add to it?

00:23:33.558 --> 00:23:34.593
IVAN: Survival.

00:23:34.593 --> 00:23:40.908
TALIESIN: Survival? Where is survival? 19!

00:23:40.908 --> 00:23:42.089
MATT: All right.

00:23:42.089 --> 00:23:42.908
ASHLY: Finally.

00:23:42.908 --> 00:23:44.169
IVAN: Don't screw this up.

00:23:44.169 --> 00:23:48.990
MATT: And with this, Mezek, for as far as goblin
franticness is concerned, manages to medicate

00:23:48.990 --> 00:23:56.651
himself with various alcohols to a state of
concentration, pushes forward deeper into the

00:23:56.651 --> 00:24:00.794
forest, against your better judgement. But in
doing so, stays out from the rainfall, manages to

00:24:00.794 --> 00:24:05.121
avoid a lot of the lightning storm which is now
blowing over the southern portion of the mountain

00:24:05.121 --> 00:24:09.649
range and leads you guys, over the next couple
hours, through a bit of a muddy, sloshy forest

00:24:09.649 --> 00:24:13.854
terrain towards the outskirts of the actual town.

00:24:13.854 --> 00:24:16.928
IVAN: Is it still night, or is it still--

00:24:16.928 --> 00:24:21.958
MATT: Oh no, it's about mid-day now, it's
pushing-- you're pushing into, like, the early

00:24:21.958 --> 00:24:25.522
afternoon at this point. You've lost a few hours
on your journey.

00:24:25.522 --> 00:24:32.534
TALIESIN: There! I only take about two hours of
responsibility today, and I'm done! It's someone

00:24:32.534 --> 00:24:34.201
else's problem now!

00:24:34.201 --> 00:24:38.245
PHIL: I will lead, now that I can see where I'm
going!

00:24:38.245 --> 00:24:41.617
IVAN: Hey, let's do the circle thing again! That
was fun!

00:24:41.617 --> 00:24:43.619
MARISHA: That was fun, like a game.

00:24:43.619 --> 00:24:47.399
TALIESIN: Was that fun? Because I've experienced what
I thought was fun before, and it was nothing like that!

00:24:47.399 --> 00:24:49.984
PHIL: Most of my fun does not hurt quite so much.

00:24:49.984 --> 00:24:52.079
IVAN: As they say, "No pain, no gain!"

00:24:52.079 --> 00:24:54.834
PHIL: I don't like the ones who say that.

00:24:54.834 --> 00:24:57.287
MATT: All right, guys--

00:24:57.287 --> 00:24:59.412
IVAN: As they say, "No pain, no shame."

00:24:59.412 --> 00:25:02.662
PHIL: I think they just like to rhyme.

00:25:02.662 --> 00:25:08.986
MATT: Following Mezek's path, you eventually make
your way through the forest, alongside the

00:25:08.986 --> 00:25:14.803
southern side of the Lost Coast Road, coming upon
the edge of the trees, to the Tyrandarock River.

00:25:14.803 --> 00:25:21.393
It surrounds the town of Sandpoint itself and
encompasses it. It's a port town that's set on the

00:25:21.393 --> 00:25:25.441
ocean, and this river surrounds the outskirts of
it. So you find the edge. You hit the muddy banks

00:25:25.441 --> 00:25:29.478
of this river, and looking across you can see now
the actual city proper.

00:25:29.478 --> 00:25:33.454
PHIL: Browntooth is very into city planning so
this is very interesting.

00:25:33.454 --> 00:25:35.506
(laughter)

00:25:35.506 --> 00:25:38.415
IVAN: I'm into city burning. That's my favorite.

00:25:38.415 --> 00:25:41.049
MARISHA: Especially if they're human cities.

00:25:41.049 --> 00:25:42.293
PHIL: Yes!

00:25:42.293 --> 00:25:48.805
IVAN: Burning, burning. So, I think because my
survival ability is so amazing, I'd like to

00:25:48.805 --> 00:25:55.789
propose that I try to fashion some sort of
flotsam, with Zarongel's guidance, I would like to

00:25:55.789 --> 00:26:02.378
try to take some flotsam and make some type of
floaty-pushy thing, that we might wade the wiver--

00:26:02.378 --> 00:26:03.561
wade the river.

00:26:03.561 --> 00:26:04.817
ASHLY: "Wade the wiver"?

00:26:04.817 --> 00:26:11.038
IVAN: Wade the wiver! To get across to the city.
Not even bothering to look for a bridge.

00:26:11.038 --> 00:26:13.038
MATT: Sure.

00:26:13.038 --> 00:26:16.288
MARISHA: You know we don't use no dirty human-made
contraptions.

00:26:16.288 --> 00:26:19.948
ASHLY: Wait, wait, wait, why don't we just swim?!

00:26:19.948 --> 00:26:29.682
MARISHA: No, no, no, look: the Snizz can do a lot
of things. The Snizz does not swim. Not very

00:26:29.682 --> 00:26:31.288
confident in my swimming abilities.

00:26:31.288 --> 00:26:33.135
PHIL: I'm not sure the Snizz can do a lot of things!

00:26:33.135 --> 00:26:34.615
(thunder)

00:26:34.615 --> 00:26:37.538
IVAN: Oh, Zarongel smiles on us again, yay.

00:26:37.538 --> 00:26:39.682
MATT: As you guys glance from the flash--

00:26:39.682 --> 00:26:41.818
IVAN: Smite another tree, Zarongel! Sorry.

00:26:41.818 --> 00:26:45.949
MATT: It's okay. You see the bolt of lightning
strike a distant watchtower on the far side of the

00:26:45.949 --> 00:26:49.243
city that has a rod specifically to pull these
types of things out of the way.

00:26:49.243 --> 00:26:50.682
IVAN: Stupid idea.

00:26:50.682 --> 00:26:54.542
MATT: Glancing over, I'll have you guys roll a
perception check if you could. Everybody go ahead

00:26:54.542 --> 00:26:56.443
and roll perception.

00:26:56.443 --> 00:27:03.500
IVAN: Solid 17.

00:27:03.500 --> 00:27:08.007
ASHLY: 17.

00:27:08.007 --> 00:27:09.171
PHIL: Ten.

00:27:09.171 --> 00:27:10.509
TALIESIN: Natural one!

00:27:10.509 --> 00:27:11.861
MATT: Marisha?

00:27:11.861 --> 00:27:13.118
MARISHA: Ten.

00:27:13.118 --> 00:27:14.615
IVAN: 17.

00:27:14.615 --> 00:27:19.637
MATT: All right, so we got two 17s here, from you guys.
Al right, so as you guys are glancing about, you

00:27:19.637 --> 00:27:24.045
can see the city before you and it generally loses
most interest to all of you, especially Mezek,

00:27:24.045 --> 00:27:27.774
who, while your direction sense has been great
today, once you get to the actual location of your

00:27:27.774 --> 00:27:32.093
intent, you've lost all interest and you're
playing in the mud. The thick clay on the side of

00:27:32.093 --> 00:27:34.050
the river smeared on your face.

00:27:34.050 --> 00:27:36.397
IVAN: I want to kick any sculptures that he makes
out of mud.

00:27:36.397 --> 00:27:37.656
MATT: Okay.

00:27:37.656 --> 00:27:39.129
PHIL: Make sure it's mud!

00:27:39.129 --> 00:27:43.006
IVAN: Whatcha going to do about it, Mezek, whatcha
going to do about it?

00:27:43.006 --> 00:27:45.088
TALIESIN: Wait 'til you're asleep.

00:27:45.088 --> 00:27:53.186
MATT: Now you're not sure if it was mud because it
spooked you a little. So, the two of you glance

00:27:53.186 --> 00:27:57.717
over and you can see there are two bridges that
lead to the city itself that go over, but both of

00:27:57.717 --> 00:28:01.424
them look extremely heavily guarded. You have two
passes of three sets of guards that walk back and

00:28:01.424 --> 00:28:08.573
forth, armed with crossbows. You guys do-- As the
midday rain is still pouring down and it's causing

00:28:08.573 --> 00:28:13.175
the surface of the river to spatter, you can see
there's a little bit of what would have been a

00:28:13.175 --> 00:28:16.469
morning marine fog that's been burning off
since it went out there so it's no longer really

00:28:16.469 --> 00:28:23.719
at your disposal. However, you two do notice,
right across the river against the bank before it

00:28:23.719 --> 00:28:30.878
rises up to the top of the city itself, you see,
barely visible, the outside of a metal grate. Some

00:28:30.878 --> 00:28:37.969
sort of a subterranean sewer or tunnel system that
is sealed shut across the way. It's a good, say,

00:28:37.969 --> 00:28:43.488
80 to 100 feet across that river right now and it
does have quite the current to it, probably

00:28:43.488 --> 00:28:45.515
because the rain's been pouring for most of the
morning.

00:28:45.515 --> 00:28:48.045
IVAN: Goblins plus sewers equals awesome.

00:28:48.045 --> 00:28:51.241
MATT: Smart one here, doing the math.

00:28:51.241 --> 00:28:55.965
IVAN: Yes. So we have to wade the river in order
to get to the grate?

00:28:55.965 --> 00:28:58.960
MATT: What do you want to do to get there? It's up
to you guys.

00:28:58.960 --> 00:29:00.636
ASHLY: Do we have to go to the grate?

00:29:00.636 --> 00:29:01.811
MATT: You don't have to.

00:29:01.811 --> 00:29:06.888
ASHLY: I don't like lightning, and I really want
to use my hammer. As a result. Those two things

00:29:06.888 --> 00:29:08.696
are connected, don't question.

00:29:08.696 --> 00:29:10.438
PHIL: Can you swim with your hammer?

00:29:10.438 --> 00:29:12.401
ASHLY: I just want to smash the dudes guarding the
bridge.

00:29:12.401 --> 00:29:16.811
PHIL: Are there guards on both bridges? Are there
guards on both bridges?

00:29:16.811 --> 00:29:18.388
MATT: Yes.

00:29:18.388 --> 00:29:27.266
IVAN: Look, I think, just putting it out there,
that grate is really, really good because there's

00:29:27.266 --> 00:29:31.495
no people in there. And humans are dumb-dumbs.

00:29:31.495 --> 00:29:35.112
ASHLY: Are you not goblins?! Do you not like
smashing humans' skulls?!

00:29:35.112 --> 00:29:41.109
IVAN: I like, pewpewpew human's skulls. I don't
like to get in all up in the face thing, Piglet.

00:29:41.109 --> 00:29:43.083
ASHLY: I think he's a coward!

00:29:43.083 --> 00:29:53.045
IVAN: How dare you call Grizznak the Great a
coward! And I want to-- I don't have magic mouth--

00:29:53.045 --> 00:29:58.192
I want to Grease her. I want to cover her in
grease.

00:29:58.192 --> 00:30:00.245
PHIL: Who doesn't?

00:30:00.245 --> 00:30:02.479
TALIESIN: This got weird quick. All right.

00:30:02.479 --> 00:30:05.599
ASHLY: Do I roll to not get greased?

00:30:05.599 --> 00:30:08.500
PHIL: We dive in the brambles and then begin to
grease each other.

00:30:08.500 --> 00:30:13.681
MATT: It has started. The game has indeed
started.

00:30:13.681 --> 00:30:18.257
IVAN: "I will show you true power!" As grease
spurts out from my hand.

00:30:18.257 --> 00:30:20.505
ASHLY: I will roll against grease.

00:30:20.505 --> 00:30:26.421
MATT: Yes, for you, I need you to make a reflex
saving throw. So go ahead and roll a d20 and add

00:30:26.421 --> 00:30:27.547
your reflex.

00:30:27.547 --> 00:30:31.012
ASHLY: 19, I will have you know. Plus my reflex.

00:30:31.012 --> 00:30:33.000
TALIESIN: There's a little box right there.

00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:34.283
ASHLY: Oh, five.

00:30:34.283 --> 00:30:35.558
MATT: You rolled a 19?

00:30:35.558 --> 00:30:36.710
ASHLY: 19 plus five.

00:30:36.710 --> 00:30:38.096
PHIL: Yeah, she rolled a 19.

00:30:38.096 --> 00:30:42.919
MATT: You go and (raspberry noise) begin to spew
grease from the outside of your goblin staff--

00:30:42.919 --> 00:30:50.325
Piglet, however, a little ball of anger and
muscular rage, instead darts out of the way,

00:30:50.325 --> 00:30:54.605
slamming into the side of the sandbank that you
are currently playing in the mud and clay with,

00:30:54.605 --> 00:31:00.209
causing that to collapse partially onto you. You
are now partially buried under the clay. And what

00:31:00.209 --> 00:31:03.190
little bit of your head is pointing out is now
being sprayed with grease.

00:31:03.190 --> 00:31:07.254
TALIESIN: (sputters, coughs)

00:31:07.254 --> 00:31:19.773
IVAN: Oh, sorry. That was meant for Piglet. Okay.
High five! All is forgiven.

00:31:19.773 --> 00:31:23.260
PHIL: I say we do the opposite of whatever he
wants to do.

00:31:23.260 --> 00:31:26.349
ASHLY: So we're going to get the humans! We're
going to smash 'em with hammers and other sharp--

00:31:26.349 --> 00:31:28.638
TALIESIN: We're supposed to be stealthy, can we do
it and be stealthy?

00:31:28.638 --> 00:31:30.336
IVAN: I think stealth is better.

00:31:30.336 --> 00:31:32.583
TALIESIN: Is there a way to smash humans with
stealth?

00:31:32.583 --> 00:31:35.552
PHIL: How many guards are there?

00:31:35.552 --> 00:31:39.556
MATT: Looking, there's about six to each bridge
that you can see.

00:31:39.556 --> 00:31:44.165
ASHLY: Can I tell if it's more advantageous for
any reason to go through the bridge

00:31:44.165 --> 00:31:46.158
versus the sewer?

00:31:46.158 --> 00:31:47.419
IVAN: Combat.

00:31:47.419 --> 00:31:56.054
MATT: It's hard to say. A town full of people--
make an intelligence check.

00:31:56.054 --> 00:31:57.809
Go ahead and roll a d20.

00:31:57.809 --> 00:31:59.637
ASHLY: This is not going to go well!

00:31:59.637 --> 00:32:01.909
IVAN: Roll for comedy.

00:32:01.909 --> 00:32:03.870
ASHLY: One!

00:32:03.870 --> 00:32:06.990
MATT: Natural one. What?

00:32:06.990 --> 00:32:08.390
ASHLY: Ten. Ten altogether.

00:32:08.390 --> 00:32:19.325
MATT: Ten altogether? Okay. So you know humans.
You know them pretty well. And they're tall, but

00:32:19.325 --> 00:32:24.750
they're pretty weak. There's a lot of them on
these bridges. That's a lot of really, really weak

00:32:24.750 --> 00:32:33.413
things. Conversely, in the sewer, who knows what's
in there? There's filth, there's scavenging

00:32:33.413 --> 00:32:42.348
pieces, and possibly dirty humans. So it's up to
you. Do you want to go out in a delightful goblin

00:32:42.348 --> 00:32:47.700
blaze of glory? Or do you want to go out in a
delightfully messy goblin blaze of glory?

00:32:47.700 --> 00:32:50.063
ASHLY: The disembodied voice makes a good point,
let's go in the sewer.

00:32:50.063 --> 00:32:53.034
(laughter)

00:32:53.034 --> 00:32:55.696
PHIL: Right! Let's drown rather than be stabbed!

00:32:55.696 --> 00:32:57.375
MARISHA: How are we going to cross?

00:32:57.375 --> 00:32:59.595
IVAN: Drowning is the way Zarongel would want us
to go out.

00:32:59.595 --> 00:33:02.369
PHIL: I thought you were going to build us some
flotsam-floaty-flotsam.

00:33:02.369 --> 00:33:07.091
MARISHA: I'm really nervous about water. I like
burning things.

00:33:07.091 --> 00:33:08.453
ASHLY: I can carry you, I'm strong.

00:33:08.453 --> 00:33:11.131
TALIESIN: I want to look around and see if there's
anything to add to this flotsam pile.

00:33:11.131 --> 00:33:12.667
MATT: Sure, make a survival check.

00:33:12.667 --> 00:33:16.902
IVAN: Can Snizzler and Mezek help me to--

00:33:16.902 --> 00:33:18.258
MARISHA: Build a rough raft.

00:33:18.258 --> 00:33:19.403
IVAN: Yeah, to build a rough raft.

00:33:19.403 --> 00:33:20.384
TALIESIN: Seven.

00:33:20.384 --> 00:33:21.651
MARISHA: I roll as well.

00:33:21.651 --> 00:33:23.510
IVAN: 17.

00:33:23.510 --> 00:33:28.313
MARISHA. What am I adding here? Don't I have 
good stuff for tinkering?

00:33:28.313 --> 00:33:32.038
IVAN: Do you want to tinker? I think this is
survival.

00:33:32.038 --> 00:33:34.944
MARISHA: Oh, survival. Ten. But he rolled pretty
good.

00:33:34.944 --> 00:33:40.351
MATT: Okay, it takes you guys the better part of
about 30 minutes or so as you find things in the

00:33:40.351 --> 00:33:44.638
nearby edge of the woods. You start pulling up the
bits of clay and sand that you were buried under

00:33:44.638 --> 00:33:47.951
as something caught your foot, and it was a bit
pointy but you found a chunk of driftwood that looks

00:33:47.951 --> 00:33:52.825
to have made its way there. I would like you all
to make a stealth check, as you are now having to

00:33:52.825 --> 00:33:55.869
dart in and out of the forest to find material.

00:33:55.869 --> 00:34:02.006
ASHLY: 18 plus 14.

00:34:02.006 --> 00:34:04.630
PHIL: Three plus 20.

00:34:04.630 --> 00:34:08.257
MATT: Plus 20?! Goblins! Oh my god.

00:34:08.257 --> 00:34:11.212
TALIESIN: 36. Damn!

00:34:11.212 --> 00:34:12.460
MARISHA: 32.

00:34:12.460 --> 00:34:13.431
IVAN: 33.

00:34:13.431 --> 00:34:18.511
MATT: Okay! You guys deftly, running back and
forth along the bank of river, grabbing

00:34:18.511 --> 00:34:23.206
what you can out of the sand and the dirt,
apparently entirely unnoticed as there even is a

00:34:23.206 --> 00:34:29.939
series of guards that come by, four of them, that
just walk on past. One of them you swear stared into

00:34:29.939 --> 00:34:31.977
the forest right at you and went--

00:34:31.977 --> 00:34:35.010
MARISHA: Be garden gnomes you guys, garden
gnomes!

00:34:35.010 --> 00:34:40.266
MATT: "Hey, Steven! Did you leave some gnomes out
here? Stupid gnomes."

00:34:40.266 --> 00:34:42.346
And they keep on walking past.

00:34:42.346 --> 00:34:45.363
MARISHA: Haha, garden gnome act gets 'em every
time! Heh, heh, heh.

00:34:45.363 --> 00:34:53.400
MATT: "Wait, I want some garden gnomes!" And he
comes back in. "Nah, they look filthy. All green.

00:34:53.400 --> 00:34:57.322
"From the mold. Stupid garden gnomes." And he keeps
going.

00:34:57.322 --> 00:35:02.027
IVAN: He's the first one that's going to get
pew-pewed.

00:35:02.027 --> 00:35:04.668
MARISHA: I agree. Boom-boom! Heh.

00:35:04.668 --> 00:35:06.282
IVAN: Boom-boom, pew-pew.

00:35:06.282 --> 00:35:08.776
TALIESIN: Two arms, two legs, one head, we'll find
him at the end.

00:35:08.776 --> 00:35:12.814
IVAN: I've got his face. I've got his beady face.

00:35:12.814 --> 00:35:19.271
MATT: So you've crafted this "raft". It's less of
a raft and more of a pool noodle buoy thing.

00:35:19.271 --> 00:35:25.343
IVAN: Yes! Yes, let's all get on a pool noodle
which is basically a giant branch.

00:35:25.343 --> 00:35:30.380
PHIL: That's the first smart thing you've said all
day!

00:35:30.380 --> 00:35:37.248
MATT: This is less like Tom Hanks in Castaway,
more Gollum in the river. You guys are having to

00:35:37.248 --> 00:35:42.107
hold on and move across. However, as you push it
into the water, it is buoyant and it does seem to

00:35:42.107 --> 00:35:47.558
carry you. The current does tend to push it, so
you guys are going to have to guide it across the

00:35:47.558 --> 00:35:51.496
current. If I could have you all make a swim
check.

00:35:51.496 --> 00:35:56.182
MARISHA: Oh, I'm so bad at this! I'm really not
the best swimmer, you guys.

00:35:56.182 --> 00:35:57.348
ASHLY: 11.

00:35:57.348 --> 00:36:01.223
MARISHA: Oh boy, this is so bad!

00:36:01.223 --> 00:36:02.511
MATT: Five?

00:36:02.511 --> 00:36:05.758
PHIL: 12.

00:36:05.758 --> 00:36:07.381
TALIESIN: 21.

00:36:07.381 --> 00:36:17.184
MARISHA: Four. I have a fear of swimming.

00:36:17.184 --> 00:36:19.882
PHIL: Sorry, 17.

00:36:19.882 --> 00:36:26.617
MATT: 17, okay. So you guys are pushing along. The
three of you are back to back, feels like goblin

00:36:26.617 --> 00:36:28.010
power, getting in there.

00:36:28.010 --> 00:36:30.684
PHIL: Oh, I swallowed a fish! (cough)

00:36:30.684 --> 00:36:32.337
TALIESIN: Share! Share!

00:36:32.337 --> 00:36:35.332
MATT: You glance over your shoulder and see the
two of them going, (yelling).

00:36:35.332 --> 00:36:37.091
IVAN and MARISHA: (yelling)

00:36:37.091 --> 00:36:39.774
MARISHA: I hate water!

00:36:39.774 --> 00:36:43.012
PHIL: Our fearless leaders!

00:36:43.012 --> 00:36:45.123
ASHLY: That feels perfectly appropriate.

00:36:45.123 --> 00:36:48.788
MATT: As part of the screaming echoes out, you
hear someone in the distance go,

00:36:48.788 --> 00:36:50.242
"D'you hear that?"

00:36:50.242 --> 00:36:52.236
ASHLY: Shut up! Shut up!

00:36:52.236 --> 00:36:53.572
IVAN: (screams quietly)

00:36:53.572 --> 00:36:56.131
MARISHA: (hyperventilates quietly)

00:36:56.131 --> 00:37:05.980
MATT: Okay. You guys stop moving and the current
carries you, and you slowly begin to rotate in the

00:37:05.980 --> 00:37:12.009
water and you're being rained on in the face. And
you see a couple guards look as you drift under

00:37:12.009 --> 00:37:18.015
the bridge on the far left side of where you
entered and they look down and go, "Man, they'll

00:37:18.015 --> 00:37:25.679
"throw away anything these days. Perfectly good
piece of wood." As it drifts under the bridge, you

00:37:25.679 --> 00:37:31.137
guys have a moment to go ahead and try and push to
shore. Go ahead and roll swim checks again.

00:37:31.137 --> 00:37:32.527
MARISHA: I'm so afraid.

00:37:32.527 --> 00:37:33.667
IVAN: Better.

00:37:33.667 --> 00:37:35.468
TALIESIN: 16.

00:37:35.468 --> 00:37:36.957
IVAN: 20.

00:37:36.957 --> 00:37:38.458
MARISHA: Negative one.

00:37:38.458 --> 00:37:40.161
MATT: Haha! It's okay.

00:37:40.161 --> 00:37:41.634
PHIL: What, are you made of lead?!

00:37:41.634 --> 00:37:45.973
MARISHA: I have a negative four swim, I just
want to point that out. (cries)

00:37:45.973 --> 00:37:53.492
MATT: So as you're pushing there, you're making
headway, except for the fact that Snizzler is

00:37:53.492 --> 00:37:57.153
going like, (yelling) and pushing your heads
under, trying to climb out of the water.

00:37:57.153 --> 00:38:00.141
IVAN: Stop it! Stop! Stop it!

00:38:00.141 --> 00:38:05.012
ASHLY: I say we kill her. We cut our losses? What?
Am I right?

00:38:05.012 --> 00:38:07.820
PHIL: Let's just knock her out, we'll need someone
to carry all of her stuff.

00:38:07.820 --> 00:38:09.413
ASHLY: I can carry it! I'm strong!

00:38:09.413 --> 00:38:13.012
MATT: As the splashing and chaos hits, you guys
(impact noise) hit the sandbank on the other side

00:38:13.012 --> 00:38:15.740
of the river. You have managed to cross it
primarily.

00:38:15.740 --> 00:38:22.947
MARISHA: Snizzler vomits. As soon as he hits land
(vomit noises).

00:38:22.947 --> 00:38:26.393
TALIESIN: I want to go through the vomit to see if
there's anything interesting in there.

00:38:26.393 --> 00:38:29.074
IVAN: I was going to say I'm-- I fight to get to
the vomit.

00:38:29.074 --> 00:38:30.299
TALIESIN: Yeah we'll fight, we'll fight.

00:38:30.299 --> 00:38:31.455
IVAN: We'll fight for the vomit.

00:38:31.455 --> 00:38:34.626
MATT: I want both of you guys to roll initiative
to see who gets to the vomit first.

00:38:34.626 --> 00:38:35.619
IVAN: Fuck!

00:38:35.619 --> 00:38:36.945
TALIESIN: What's-- oh. 11.

00:38:36.945 --> 00:38:38.622
MATT: What did you get?

00:38:38.622 --> 00:38:40.326
IVAN: I got 11!

00:38:40.326 --> 00:38:42.665
MATT: You guys both--

00:38:42.665 --> 00:38:44.421
PHIL: Conk!

00:38:44.421 --> 00:38:48.855
TALIESIN: (cackling) (raspberry noise)

00:38:48.855 --> 00:38:53.658
MATT: And with that, Mezek grabs a hand scoop up
of this crusted sand--

00:38:53.658 --> 00:38:55.039
TALIESIN: I have a jug.

00:38:55.039 --> 00:38:58.142
MATT: Puts it in the jug. Closes it off.

00:38:58.142 --> 00:38:59.921
TALIESIN: I'll go through it later.

00:38:59.921 --> 00:39:01.630
IVAN: Being a goblin is amazing.

00:39:01.630 --> 00:39:11.394
MATT: At which point you hear another voice say,
"Did you hear laughing? I'm going to go check."

00:39:11.394 --> 00:39:13.434
And you hear a number of footsteps coming your
way.

00:39:13.434 --> 00:39:15.441
IVAN: I'm going to cast Ghost Sound.

00:39:15.441 --> 00:39:16.365
MATT: Okay.

00:39:16.365 --> 00:39:18.840
IVAN: To see if I can distract them away.

00:39:18.840 --> 00:39:20.474
MATT: What kind of sound are you producing?

00:39:20.474 --> 00:39:25.948
IVAN: I'm going to produce a righteous
merriment-making sound.

00:39:25.948 --> 00:39:29.293
MATT: On the direction of...?

00:39:29.293 --> 00:39:31.863
IVAN: It sounds like drunken storytelling.

00:39:31.863 --> 00:39:38.780
MATT: Okay. So, at this point you guys watch as
Grizznak spins around, points his staff forward,

00:39:38.780 --> 00:39:46.030
and quite a ways away you hear this boisterous
(indistinct drunk storytelling) start blasting

00:39:46.030 --> 00:39:51.156
from the opposite side of the bridge, up near the
rocks that begin to meet the base of

00:39:51.156 --> 00:39:56.116
the city's foundation. The footsteps shift and you
hear them going across the wood planks above you

00:39:56.116 --> 00:40:01.490
on the bridge, in the direction that he set. Now
is your time to go ahead and dart for the

00:40:01.490 --> 00:40:06.488
grate on the outside of the sewer. Go ahead and roll
stealth checks, all you guys.

00:40:06.488 --> 00:40:07.770
IVAN: Stealth checks?

00:40:07.770 --> 00:40:09.221
TALIESIN: That's leaning.

00:40:09.221 --> 00:40:10.943
ASHLY: 23.

00:40:10.943 --> 00:40:12.065
MATT: 23?

00:40:12.065 --> 00:40:13.259
PHIL: 40.

00:40:13.259 --> 00:40:17.691
MATT: Jesus! You vanish from time and space!

00:40:17.691 --> 00:40:20.534
TALIESIN: He folds to be one-dimensional.

00:40:20.534 --> 00:40:24.244
MATT: You have a fifth-dimensional goblin on your
team now.

00:40:24.244 --> 00:40:25.510
TALIESIN: 31.

00:40:25.510 --> 00:40:26.928
MARISHA: 19.

00:40:26.928 --> 00:40:28.144
IVAN: 22.

00:40:28.144 --> 00:40:31.194
MATT: Okay. You guys, darting through the rain,
using the edge of the rocky--

00:40:31.194 --> 00:40:33.083
PHIL: What took you so long?

00:40:33.083 --> 00:40:38.157
MATT: You get to the grate, and there is indeed
Browntooth sitting there picking his teeth with

00:40:38.157 --> 00:40:39.544
one of his blades.

00:40:39.544 --> 00:40:41.894
TALIESIN: How did he do that?

00:40:41.894 --> 00:40:43.766
ASHLY: What I don't-- you were just-- and then--

00:40:43.766 --> 00:40:47.347
PHIL: Sometimes it pays to be quiet.

00:40:47.347 --> 00:40:51.516
ASHLY: I think we all learned a valuable lesson.

00:40:51.516 --> 00:40:54.889
PHIL: Now who's going to rip off this grate?

00:40:54.889 --> 00:40:55.815
ASHLY: Me!!

00:40:55.815 --> 00:40:57.196
PHIL: Oh, god!

00:40:57.196 --> 00:41:00.127
MATT: Piglet, go ahead and make a strength check.
Roll and add your strength modifier.

00:41:00.127 --> 00:41:01.796
ASHLY: (laughing) 25.

00:41:01.796 --> 00:41:09.460
MATT: 25! With one hand, Piglet, holding the hammer
in one hand, grabs the grate, spins it in place,

00:41:09.460 --> 00:41:16.460
sending rust and metal sparks, and throws it
behind her, (sploosh).

00:41:16.460 --> 00:41:18.247
ASHLY: And I go like this.

00:41:18.247 --> 00:41:21.241
PHIL: Again, I would like to mention about the
being quiet part.

00:41:21.241 --> 00:41:27.822
IVAN: I take a moment to absorb all of that
amazing that happened right there.

00:41:27.822 --> 00:41:29.581
ASHLY: You're welcome, you're welcome.

00:41:29.581 --> 00:41:36.632
IVAN: Yeah, Grizznak, not being the strongest of
the bunch, is easily swayed by intense feats of

00:41:36.632 --> 00:41:38.022
strength. Oh, my!

00:41:38.022 --> 00:41:40.962
PHIL: Grizznak, you look like you want to grease
her again in a whole new way!

00:41:40.962 --> 00:41:47.344
IVAN: Wishes he had another Grease spell prepared!
Woo! Okay.

00:41:47.344 --> 00:41:53.975
MATT: At which point you hear the howl of distant
wind and the droplets of condensation within the

00:41:53.975 --> 00:42:02.338
depths of this sewage system beckoning to you as
an entry portal to this city. Secretly, privately,

00:42:02.338 --> 00:42:06.355
and hopefully to wherever this festival is
happening where you can gather this "Storm Rock."

00:42:06.355 --> 00:42:08.446
IVAN: Smells just like home.

00:42:08.446 --> 00:42:10.488
PHIL: Yes, moldy and clammy.

00:42:10.488 --> 00:42:16.050
IVAN: Yay. Hey, do you remember when we were in
juvie and they threw us down in the "lock box"?

00:42:16.050 --> 00:42:17.336
For like a month?

00:42:17.336 --> 00:42:19.102
MARISHA: Oh, dude, and we got so blazed.

00:42:19.102 --> 00:42:20.262
IVAN: We got so blazed!

00:42:20.262 --> 00:42:21.562
MARISHA: That was so good, man.

00:42:21.562 --> 00:42:23.096
IVAN: Yeah, this reminds me of that.

00:42:23.096 --> 00:42:24.676
MARISHA: Yeah, yeah, I agree.

00:42:24.676 --> 00:42:26.255
ASHLY: I feel excluded.

00:42:26.255 --> 00:42:27.878
(laughter)

00:42:27.878 --> 00:42:29.725
ASHLY: Remember when I ripped the grate off of the
thing?

00:42:29.725 --> 00:42:32.213
PHIL: Oh, those were the days.

00:42:32.213 --> 00:42:34.375
TALIESIN: When did that happen? I don't remember
that.

00:42:34.375 --> 00:42:36.927
IVAN: I think we're all going to want to sneak--

00:42:36.927 --> 00:42:38.281
PHIL: Let's go inside.

00:42:38.281 --> 00:42:39.524
IVAN: Sneak around inside.

00:42:39.524 --> 00:42:43.405
TALIESIN: I want to keep my eyes peeled for
things that might be useful or that can contain alcohol.

00:42:43.405 --> 00:42:49.902
MATT: Okay. Good to know. You guys step your way
inside the sewer. The slick stone structure of it

00:42:49.902 --> 00:42:58.408
has lots of residue buildup from various minerals
that have come through, as well as various degrees

00:42:58.408 --> 00:43:04.839
of wastewater that have found their way to the
river. The smell is horrible for anyone but you

00:43:04.839 --> 00:43:13.430
guys. It's a familiar scent. As you make your way
inside-- I'd say about 100 feet in as you're going

00:43:13.430 --> 00:43:18.400
through the darkness here-- but you guys can see
fine in the dark, this is goblin speciality.

00:43:18.400 --> 00:43:20.285
IVAN: Darkvision, guys.

00:43:20.285 --> 00:43:24.875
PHIL: I check to see if there are any insects that
are tasty-looking.

00:43:24.875 --> 00:43:30.088
MATT: Go ahead and make a perception check.

00:43:30.088 --> 00:43:32.525
PHIL: 21.

00:43:32.525 --> 00:43:44.234
MATT: All right. Glancing about, you do see a
cluster of some sort of an egg sac that is pushed

00:43:44.234 --> 00:43:52.804
up into the corner along the curved rotation of this
duct. It's roughly the size of a large melon. And

00:43:52.804 --> 00:43:54.358
it twitches--

00:43:54.358 --> 00:43:56.172
IVAN: I will burn it with Flare.

00:43:56.172 --> 00:43:57.192
MARISHA: Yeah!

00:43:57.192 --> 00:43:58.583
ASHLY: Don't burn it, we're going to eat it!

00:43:58.583 --> 00:44:01.627
MATT: As you're looking up at it, (fwoosh) it
bursts into flames.

00:44:01.627 --> 00:44:03.183
ASHLY: What the heck!!

00:44:03.183 --> 00:44:06.355
PHIL: Who burns food?!

00:44:06.355 --> 00:44:11.754
IVAN: Roasted spiders are best spiders. See, you
guys aren't smart, so you don't know that burning

00:44:11.754 --> 00:44:14.246
spiders makes them that much tastier.

00:44:14.246 --> 00:44:16.118
ASHLY: Are there spiders left to eat?

00:44:16.118 --> 00:44:23.417
MATT: You go and glance and the slight tiny series
of squeaks you hear as the hundreds of tiny spider

00:44:23.417 --> 00:44:31.384
young have burned to their end. There is a nice
waft of cooked scent that hits your nose. And the

00:44:31.384 --> 00:44:39.577
rumbling in your tummy takes over, as you guys all
leap in at once, grabbing small chunks of what you can.

00:44:39.577 --> 00:44:42.278
MARISHA: This is the best, when it's crispy on the
outside but gooey on the inside.

00:44:42.278 --> 00:44:44.140
PHIL: I wish there was tartar sauce.

00:44:44.140 --> 00:44:45.579
TALIESIN: "Oh wait!" I open up the jar--

00:44:45.579 --> 00:44:48.251
(horrified laughter)

00:44:48.251 --> 00:44:50.556
TALIESIN: Smear some on his spider chunk.

00:44:50.556 --> 00:44:52.083
PHIL: Close enough!

00:44:52.083 --> 00:44:56.322
IVAN: Did you season our birds spider egglettes
with vomit?

00:44:56.322 --> 00:44:59.854
ASHLY: Don't knock it. This is the good shit.

00:44:59.854 --> 00:45:01.487
IVAN: I burned it for you!

00:45:01.487 --> 00:45:03.207
TALIESIN: I won it fair and square!

00:45:03.207 --> 00:45:09.963
IVAN: I'm going to cast arcane mark on the side of
this wall and mark that we were here.

00:45:09.963 --> 00:45:17.433
Particularly, "Grizznak the Greatest was here," is
what I'm going to mark. But it really looks like a

00:45:17.433 --> 00:45:19.680
giant butt with like a cloud--

00:45:19.680 --> 00:45:21.478
TALIESIN: I was about to say, can you read and
write?

00:45:21.478 --> 00:45:22.768
PHIL: No words?

00:45:22.768 --> 00:45:29.357
IVAN: No, no words. The symbol for "Grizznak the
Greatest" is a goblin with two cheeky farts and a

00:45:29.357 --> 00:45:30.608
cloud coming out of it.

00:45:30.608 --> 00:45:32.532
TALIESIN: I was imagining a goblin dick-butt.

00:45:32.532 --> 00:45:34.065
(laughter)

00:45:34.065 --> 00:45:36.583
IVAN: That is the mark of Grizznak the Great.

00:45:36.583 --> 00:45:40.676
PHIL: A goblin dick looks like a human dick, but
with spurs.

00:45:40.676 --> 00:45:44.178
TALIESIN: Oh, god! Oh! Thank you, thank you.

00:45:44.178 --> 00:45:46.545
MATT: We learned a very valuable lesson this
evening.

00:45:46.545 --> 00:45:48.794
IVAN: Of goblin physiology.

00:45:48.794 --> 00:45:50.529
PHIL: That's how you know it's love.

00:45:50.529 --> 00:45:52.244
TALIESIN: No!

00:45:52.244 --> 00:45:53.838
MATT: Tumblr, get on that.

00:45:53.838 --> 00:45:57.317
TALIESIN: Oh, god. Too late. Moving on.

00:45:57.317 --> 00:46:00.493
PHIL: I can't unsee it in my mind!

00:46:00.493 --> 00:46:04.091
TALIESIN: You won't have to, you'll go on the internet in
about an hour, and it'll be there. There's nothing

00:46:04.091 --> 00:46:05.206
that can be done anymore.

00:46:05.206 --> 00:46:06.950
MATT: You did this, Phil. You did this.

00:46:06.950 --> 00:46:09.523
TALIESIN: We're not kidding. We're not even
kidding a little.

00:46:09.523 --> 00:46:15.228
IVAN: Oh, all right. Grizznak the Great has left
his Arcane Mark. A goblin dick-butt.

00:46:15.228 --> 00:46:19.893
MATT: Progressing forward for the next couple
hundred feet into this slick sewer, making your

00:46:19.893 --> 00:46:29.145
way along embankments where bits of clutter,
broken sticks, chunks of wayward stone and mortar

00:46:29.145 --> 00:46:37.622
pieces that have washed down here have built these
small half-walls of junk that have mucked up the side.

00:46:37.622 --> 00:46:44.426
MARISHA: Snizzler takes a firecracker that he has
and secretly lights it and throws it behind him

00:46:44.426 --> 00:46:46.306
real fast without telling anybody.

00:46:46.306 --> 00:46:55.557
MATT: Okay. You guys walk forward until
(explosion) you all glance over your shoulder real fast--

00:46:55.557 --> 00:46:57.180
TALIESIN: I attack.

00:46:57.180 --> 00:46:58.646
(laughter)

00:46:58.646 --> 00:47:00.925
MATT: Go ahead and roll an attack.

00:47:00.925 --> 00:47:02.072
TALIESIN: Thank you.

00:47:02.072 --> 00:47:04.100
IVAN: "I attack the darkness!"

00:47:04.100 --> 00:47:05.833
(laughter)

00:47:05.833 --> 00:47:07.153
TALIESIN: 14.

00:47:07.153 --> 00:47:13.178
MATT: 14, okay. You turn around real fast as a
piece of rock that is set loose from this small

00:47:13.178 --> 00:47:19.019
firecracker explosion, whips through the air and
you punch it with your fist.

00:47:19.019 --> 00:47:21.514
Go ahead and roll damage.

00:47:21.514 --> 00:47:26.200
IVAN: I forgot he's a goblin monk. He punches
things.

00:47:26.200 --> 00:47:28.179
TALIESIN: That's five.

00:47:28.179 --> 00:47:38.405
MATT: With that, you turn this piece of mildewed,
slimy, sewage-encrusted stone to dust as it (poof)

00:47:38.405 --> 00:47:43.522
in front of you. Holding your fist as it shakes
there quivering, your eyes open. Any buzz you may

00:47:43.522 --> 00:47:49.589
have carried from your morning alcohol has waned
for now and you are far more awake and conscious--

00:47:49.589 --> 00:47:51.299
with a mild headache.

00:47:51.299 --> 00:47:57.441
IVAN: Guys, we're into this campaign and so far
the only thing we've defeated is a rock. This is

00:47:57.441 --> 00:47:59.017
the best goblin campaign.

00:47:59.017 --> 00:48:00.725
(laughter)

00:48:00.725 --> 00:48:05.438
MATT: The path does split here now and divides to
the right and left.

00:48:05.438 --> 00:48:07.652
ASHLY: Can I roll perception?

00:48:07.652 --> 00:48:08.822
MATT: To see...?

00:48:08.822 --> 00:48:11.104
ASHLY: If there's anything different about them?

00:48:11.104 --> 00:48:12.620
MATT: Sure, go for it.

00:48:12.620 --> 00:48:16.730
ASHLY: 17 plus four is 21.

00:48:16.730 --> 00:48:22.265
MATT: Piglet, you're the instinctual tracker. Most
goblins hunt with traps, you hunt with teeth.

00:48:22.265 --> 00:48:23.503
ASHLY: Nice.

00:48:23.503 --> 00:48:29.375
MATT: So you get down and (sniffing) begin getting
into the muck and pushing it aside. Less than a

00:48:29.375 --> 00:48:34.555
visual perspective here, you can smell that the
bulk of the waste that comes through here comes

00:48:34.555 --> 00:48:38.532
from the left path. That probably means more
waste, means more people.

00:48:38.532 --> 00:48:41.276
IVAN: More waste, more people.

00:48:41.276 --> 00:48:43.064
PHIL: So we should go away from the people...

00:48:43.064 --> 00:48:48.866
ASHLY: Wait, what are we doing?

00:48:48.866 --> 00:48:50.218
MARISHA: Yeah, why are we here?

00:48:50.218 --> 00:48:51.917
IVAN: Get the blue stone.

00:48:51.917 --> 00:48:53.047
ASHLY: A rock! The rock!

00:48:53.047 --> 00:48:56.007
TALIESIN: The cracked man with the blue stone!

00:48:56.007 --> 00:49:00.846
ASHLY: Zachary! That's the guy, right?

00:49:00.846 --> 00:49:03.705
PHIL: He's in blue. He's got a rock.

00:49:03.705 --> 00:49:10.749
IVAN: I remember he's in a birch. Like a birch
tree. Right? Birch.

00:49:10.749 --> 00:49:12.267
TALIESIN: No, a church tree!

00:49:12.267 --> 00:49:14.090
IVAN: A church tree, that's right.

00:49:14.090 --> 00:49:19.531
MARISHA: And we stay under trees when there's
lightning. That's what you're thinking of.

00:49:19.531 --> 00:49:23.386
IVAN: Right. That's right, because Zarongel likes
to smite trees.

00:49:23.386 --> 00:49:26.358
PHIL: Do we go to the poop, or away from the
poop?

00:49:26.358 --> 00:49:29.623
ALL: To the poop!!

00:49:29.623 --> 00:49:32.159
IVAN: To the poop! So we go down the left channel.

00:49:32.159 --> 00:49:36.096
MATT: All right, so you guys-- (laughs) you charge
forward here--

00:49:36.096 --> 00:49:39.230
ASHLY: Wait, just to clarify, because I used my
teeth, does that mean I ate

00:49:39.230 --> 00:49:42.390
poop to find the tunnel?

00:49:42.390 --> 00:49:45.246
PHIL: Well, I hope you saved some for the rest of
us!

00:49:45.246 --> 00:49:51.329
MATT: No, you had to smear it on your teeth a
little. Pushing forward, you guys travel another

00:49:51.329 --> 00:50:00.055
80 or so feet before you come onto a large series of
waterfalls that run into a central open cesspool

00:50:00.055 --> 00:50:06.626
area that is down below this path. The actual path
diverts and goes around this central tunnel before

00:50:06.626 --> 00:50:10.678
it continues in a singular direction as the water
is pouring in.

00:50:10.678 --> 00:50:12.354
PHIL: What do we see above?

00:50:12.354 --> 00:50:13.780
MATT: Make a perception check.

00:50:13.780 --> 00:50:16.480
IVAN: Can I look as well?

00:50:16.480 --> 00:50:18.506
PHIL: 25.

00:50:18.506 --> 00:50:21.400
IVAN: 12.

00:50:21.400 --> 00:50:26.781
MATT: Okay. You look down into the cesspool and
hock a loogie to see how far it goes down.

00:50:26.781 --> 00:50:29.062
(splash noise)

00:50:29.062 --> 00:50:30.265
IVAN: 25 feet.

00:50:30.265 --> 00:50:31.952
TALIESIN: Those are not supposed to be solid.

00:50:31.952 --> 00:50:33.369
PHIL: And deep too. What? No.

00:50:33.369 --> 00:50:38.142
MATT: You glance up and you can see there is some
sort of a large, heavy grating that most of the

00:50:38.142 --> 00:50:43.397
water is pouring down from. You're not quite--
looks like a lot of the rainwater runoff from the

00:50:43.397 --> 00:50:49.879
city itself. However, you do notice a glimmer from
what little bit of light that is bouncing through

00:50:49.879 --> 00:50:54.063
from the surface and your goblin eyes catch this
little glimmer in the corner and you glance over

00:50:54.063 --> 00:50:56.725
and instinctually run towards it. You go ahead
and take a look.

00:50:56.725 --> 00:50:58.014
PHIL: It's shiny.

00:50:58.014 --> 00:51:03.743
MATT: You find a
hefty well-made human shortsword.

00:51:03.743 --> 00:51:06.726
PHIL: Dibs.

00:51:06.726 --> 00:51:08.392
IVAN: So it's a broadsword for you.

00:51:08.392 --> 00:51:10.805
PHIL: Are you saying I'm small?

00:51:10.805 --> 00:51:12.520
IVAN: I'm saying we're all small.

00:51:12.520 --> 00:51:13.636
PHIL: Oh, right.

00:51:13.636 --> 00:51:16.896
MATT: What did you roll? What was the total on
your perception check again?

00:51:16.896 --> 00:51:18.014
PHIL: 25.

00:51:18.014 --> 00:51:24.546
MATT: 25. You take this and the blade is 
perfectly clean. This place is filthy. This blade

00:51:24.546 --> 00:51:27.961
is perfectly clean, and as you glance over
underneath the waterfall you see another glimmer.

00:51:27.961 --> 00:51:34.392
PHIL: Ooh! I run and go over there. I carry the
sword with me. I don't trust these two.

00:51:34.392 --> 00:51:36.705
TALIESIN: I see that he is. I'm approaching
cautiously.

00:51:36.705 --> 00:51:39.819
ASHLY: I want to push everyone else away and get
there first.

00:51:39.819 --> 00:51:42.885
PHIL: Hey wait, you can't even see it, can you?

00:51:42.885 --> 00:51:45.195
MATT: Both of you guys make initiative checks
right now.

00:51:45.195 --> 00:51:48.114
ASHLY: 11.

00:51:48.114 --> 00:51:49.316
PHIL: Four.

00:51:49.316 --> 00:51:50.785
TALIESIN: Wait, you got plus six.

00:51:50.785 --> 00:51:51.816
PHIL: Ten.

00:51:51.816 --> 00:51:53.978
ASHLY: Oh wait. 15.

00:51:53.978 --> 00:51:58.204
MATT: So as you see this and you glance over out
of the corner of your eye, you see Piglet. Her

00:51:58.204 --> 00:52:04.087
eyes go wide and both of you have that immediate
knowledge of "me first". You both dart off around

00:52:04.087 --> 00:52:10.441
two different sides of this cistern and starting
to get there. However, Piglet, you get there first

00:52:10.441 --> 00:52:15.235
and immediately leap towards this shiny. And the
shiny is bigger than you expected.

00:52:15.235 --> 00:52:19.785
IVAN: Can I cast Mage Hand to see if I can snatch
it from all three of them or

00:52:19.785 --> 00:52:21.463
away from the two of them?

00:52:21.463 --> 00:52:23.272
MATT: Is it a five-pound maximum?

00:52:23.272 --> 00:52:24.471
IVAN: Five pounds, yeah.

00:52:24.471 --> 00:52:28.547
MATT: You go ahead and cast Mage Hand towards that
shiny and pull and (grunts) it's a little heavier

00:52:28.547 --> 00:52:33.867
than you can pull. You get there and you grab on
to it. What you notice as you get there is a set,

00:52:33.867 --> 00:52:41.399
a full set, of a breastplate armor. Human size,
giant breastplate with some shoulder pauldrons and

00:52:41.399 --> 00:52:45.022
a human ribcage on the inside of this
breastplate.

00:52:45.022 --> 00:52:46.534
ASHLY: Ooh! Ribcage.

00:52:46.534 --> 00:52:50.228
MATT: You smell it. Marrow hasn't been tapped
yet.

00:52:50.228 --> 00:52:52.947
ASHLY: Can I eat it?

00:52:52.947 --> 00:52:54.297
MATT: You can.

00:52:54.297 --> 00:52:55.972
ASHLY: I eat it.

00:52:55.972 --> 00:52:57.247
PHIL: Barbeque.

00:52:57.247 --> 00:52:58.814
ASHLY: Can I wear the armor? Is it too big for
me?

00:52:58.814 --> 00:53:01.559
MATT: It's pretty big, yeah. You could sleep in
it.

00:53:01.559 --> 00:53:04.265
PHIL: Rent it out!

00:53:04.265 --> 00:53:09.786
MATT: So you grab the ribcage, break off a couple
ribs, start gnawing on them, sucking the marrow

00:53:09.786 --> 00:53:17.781
out. You do notice, getting there and inspecting,
the ribcage is white. It is clean as well. You can

00:53:17.781 --> 00:53:23.396
see, upon close look as she is gnawing, not even
paying attention, you see these little teeth marks

00:53:23.396 --> 00:53:27.734
on it like rats have come through here and there.
Overall, the bone is perfectly clean. The armor

00:53:27.734 --> 00:53:31.500
itself is spotless, looks like it's been perfectly
polished.

00:53:31.500 --> 00:53:37.049
ASHLY: This marrow's real good. You guys are
missing out.

00:53:37.049 --> 00:53:39.143
MARISHA: Pass me a rib.

00:53:39.143 --> 00:53:46.522
PHIL: Is there any of the armor that any of us can
fit?

00:53:46.522 --> 00:53:52.063
MATT: You could try and pull scrap from it if you
wanted to try and scavenge pieces of the metal.

00:53:52.063 --> 00:53:55.974
TALIESIN: If we pulled the two shoulder pieces
off, could we maybe tie them together and wear

00:53:55.974 --> 00:53:58.184
them like an Eat at Joe's sign?

00:53:58.184 --> 00:54:00.473
MATT: Could certainly try that if you want to,
yes.

00:54:00.473 --> 00:54:01.869
TALIESIN: I'm going to give it a roll.

00:54:01.869 --> 00:54:08.474
MATT: Okay. I will say for this-- you know what,
go ahead and make a survival check

00:54:08.474 --> 00:54:09.906
on this to try and--

00:54:09.906 --> 00:54:14.941
TALIESIN: That's funny. No, I'm down. 12.

00:54:14.941 --> 00:54:21.105
MATT: 12. You manage to (grunt) for a minute, with
some help from a couple other of the goblins, pull

00:54:21.105 --> 00:54:24.085
one of the pauldrons off. You take it and--

00:54:24.085 --> 00:54:26.751
PHIL: Don't choke yourself!

00:54:26.751 --> 00:54:34.999
MATT: Based on your combat aesthetic, it's not
going to be much of a help to you.

00:54:34.999 --> 00:54:41.186
IVAN: This is-- I never thought I would hear a
goblin character say this, but I can spellcraft to

00:54:41.186 --> 00:54:43.154
check to see if it's magical at all?

00:54:43.154 --> 00:54:44.163
MATT: Sure. The armor?

00:54:44.163 --> 00:54:45.104
IVAN: The armor.

00:54:45.104 --> 00:54:46.289
MATT: Yeah. Go for it.

00:54:46.289 --> 00:54:54.135
IVAN: I almost want to kick it into the cistern to
get it dirty. I'm sorry. I don't know why I

00:54:54.135 --> 00:54:57.526
rolled because I'm doing spellcraft. Yes, that's
right. 19.

00:54:57.526 --> 00:55:02.912
MATT: The armor itself does not appear to have a
magical essence to it. In fact, a close look--

00:55:02.912 --> 00:55:08.383
it's pretty close to the design of armor the
guards were wearing on the actual bridge itself.

00:55:08.383 --> 00:55:13.842
It's just completely polished down here in the middle
of a dank sewer.

00:55:13.842 --> 00:55:16.836
ASHLY: Does the armor help any of the rest of us?
The goblin-crafted?

00:55:16.893 --> 00:55:20.501
TALIESIN: I'm going to throw it at Piglet. Just
throw it at you.

00:55:20.501 --> 00:55:22.230
MATT: It's delightful decoration.

00:55:22.230 --> 00:55:24.336
ASHLY: Oh! Ho ho ho ho!

00:55:24.336 --> 00:55:31.215
IVAN: Are you Woody Woodpecker now? I think
something killed--

00:55:31.215 --> 00:55:35.386
PHIL: I think something is down here cleaning.
We've got to get out of here!

00:55:35.386 --> 00:55:37.570
Before it comes back!

00:55:37.570 --> 00:55:41.381
IVAN: I don't want whatever cleaned this armor to
clean off Grizznak the Great's fine robes.

00:55:41.381 --> 00:55:43.708
PHIL: It'll take the farts right out of you.

00:55:43.708 --> 00:55:45.780
IVAN: Is there any way to climb up to the
grate?

00:55:45.780 --> 00:55:51.147
MATT: It's about 40 feet up from you guys. The
path continues across the cistern

00:55:51.147 --> 00:55:53.167
deeper into the city.

00:55:53.167 --> 00:55:55.667
MARISHA: We didn't think about having to crawl
back out.

00:55:55.667 --> 00:55:58.575
MATT: Beyond the cistern, the tunnel continues
after it converges.

00:55:58.575 --> 00:56:00.039
PHIL: Just keep going.

00:56:00.039 --> 00:56:03.932
MATT: Who's leading this expedition now?

00:56:03.932 --> 00:56:07.180
PHIL: I think I'm more qualified to lead but I
don't like to be in front.

00:56:07.180 --> 00:56:08.575
ASHLY: I have the prettiest hat.

00:56:08.575 --> 00:56:10.731
PHIL: Piglet. I nominate you.

00:56:10.731 --> 00:56:11.870
ASHLY: Hooray!

00:56:11.870 --> 00:56:14.277
MATT: Piglet, go ahead and roll perception.

00:56:14.277 --> 00:56:19.667
ASHLY: (singing) I forget where my perception is
every time. There it is. 19.

00:56:19.667 --> 00:56:31.112
MATT: 19, okay. All righty, so as you go-- as you
put your new shiny hat on and begin stepping

00:56:31.112 --> 00:56:37.793
forward across where the paths converge. You--
big, knees forward, stomping steps and you put

00:56:37.793 --> 00:56:45.698
your head forward and stop as there's a distortion
